**Sec. 80001. Exemption of Certain Assets.**
Effective July 1, 2026, for the 2026-2027 award year and subsequent years, the Higher Education Act is amended to exclude the net value of a family farm, a small business with no more than 100 full-time employees, and a commercial fishing business from the calculation of a family's assets for federal student aid eligibility. These exemptions apply specifically to assets owned and controlled by the family residing on the farm or operating the business. This change aims to prevent families with significant non-cash assets in these specific sectors from being penalized in their financial aid determinations.

**Sec. 81001. Establishment of Loan Limits for Graduate and Professional Students and Parent Borrowers; Termination of Graduate and Professional PLUS Loans.**
Beginning July 1, 2026, the bill terminates the authority to issue interest-subsidized loans to graduate students and completely ends the issuance of Federal Direct PLUS Loans to graduate and professional students. New annual loan limits are set at $20,500 for graduate students and $50,000 for professional students, with aggregate limits capped at $100,000 for non-professional graduate students and $200,000 for professional students. Additionally, parent borrowers are restricted to a maximum annual limit of $20,000 and an aggregate limit of $65,000 per dependent student. Existing students enrolled as of June 30, 2026, are grandfathered under previous limits for up to three academic years or their expected time to credential.

**Sec. 82001. Loan Repayment.**
Starting July 1, 2026, the bill repeals Income Contingent Repayment (ICR) plans and replaces them with a new "Repayment Assistance Plan" (RAP) and a Standard Repayment Plan, requiring borrowers to choose between the two. The RAP sets monthly payments based on a sliding scale of 1% to 10% of adjusted gross income, with a minimum payment of $10, and offers loan forgiveness after 360 qualifying payments. For loans made on or after July 1, 2026, borrowers with "excepted loans" (such as Parent PLUS loans) must use the Standard Repayment Plan, while other borrowers may choose the RAP or a Standard Plan with terms ranging from 10 to 25 years based on total debt. Borrowers with existing ICR loans must transition to one of the new plans by July 1, 2028.

**Sec. 82002. Deferment; Forbearance.**
For loans originated on or after July 1, 2027, the bill eliminates eligibility for economic hardship and unemployment deferments, which previously allowed borrowers to pause payments without accruing interest. Furthermore, forbearance for these new loans is strictly limited to a maximum of 9 months within any 24-month period, replacing previous broader forbearance provisions. This restriction aims to reduce the accumulation of unpaid interest and ensure borrowers remain actively engaged in repayment.

**Sec. 82003. Loan Rehabilitation.**
Effective July 1, 2027, the bill increases the number of times a borrower may rehabilitate a defaulted FFEL or Direct loan from one time to two times, and similarly allows Perkins loan borrowers to rehabilitate their loans twice. Additionally, for loans made on or after July 1, 2027, the minimum monthly payment required for loan rehabilitation is set at $10. These changes provide borrowers with more opportunities to restore their credit standing and exit default status.

**Sec. 82004. Public Service Loan Forgiveness.**
The bill amends the Public Service Loan Forgiveness (PSLF) program to explicitly count on-time payments made under the new Repayment Assistance Plan as qualifying payments for loan forgiveness. Previously, PSLF eligibility was tied to specific income-driven plans, but this amendment ensures that borrowers on the new RAP can still work toward the 120 qualifying payments required for forgiveness. This maintains the incentive for public service employment under the revised repayment structure.

**Sec. 82005. Student Loan Servicing.**
The bill appropriates $1,000,000,000 to the Secretary of Education to cover administrative costs associated with servicing Direct student loan programs, including the costs of managing the new repayment plans. These funds are available until expended and are in addition to any other amounts appropriated for administrative costs under the Higher Education Act. This funding is intended to support the operational transition to the new repayment systems and ensure effective loan servicing.

**Sec. 83001. Eligibility.**
Beginning July 1, 2026, the bill expands the definition of adjusted gross income for Federal Pell Grant eligibility to include foreign income for both dependent and independent students. Additionally, the bill establishes a new ineligibility rule where students with a Student Aid Index (SAI) equal to or exceeding twice the maximum Federal Pell Grant amount for that year will be barred from receiving the grant. These changes aim to refine eligibility criteria and ensure grants are directed to students with the greatest financial need.

**Sec. 83002. Workforce Pell Grants.**
Starting July 1, 2026, the bill creates a new "Workforce Pell Grant" program for students enrolled in eligible workforce programs that are at least 150 clock hours but less than 600 clock hours in length. To qualify, programs must be approved by the State Governor and the Secretary of Education, demonstrating high completion rates (70%), high job placement rates (70%), and a positive value-added earnings ratio. Students in these short-term, high-skill programs can receive grants prorated based on program length, provided they do not already hold a graduate credential.

**Sec. 83003. Pell Shortfall.**
The bill increases the funding authorization for the Federal Pell Grant program's shortfall from $2,170,000,000 to $12,670,000,000 to ensure sufficient funds are available to meet demand. This significant increase is designed to prevent the program from running out of money before the end of the fiscal year, thereby protecting the eligibility of low-income students. The additional funding supports the expanded eligibility and new Workforce Pell Grant provisions.

**Sec. 83004. Federal Pell Grant Exclusion Relating to Other Grant Aid.**
Effective July 1, 2026, the bill prohibits students from receiving a Federal Pell Grant during any period where they receive non-Federal grant aid (from states, institutions, or private sources) that equals or exceeds their total cost of attendance. This exclusion prevents "double-dipping" where students receive full funding from multiple sources that together cover their entire educational expenses. The rule ensures that federal Pell funds are reserved for students who do not have their full cost of attendance covered by other non-federal sources.

**Sec. 84001. Ineligibility Based on Low Earning Outcomes.**
Beginning July 1, 2026, the bill makes institutions ineligible for federal funds for specific programs if the median earnings of their graduates are less than the median earnings of working adults with similar education levels for two out of three years. The determination compares program graduates to working adults aged 25-34 with only a high school diploma (for bachelor's programs) or a bachelor's degree (for graduate programs). Institutions must provide assurances of compliance and are subject to an appeals process, with a requirement to notify students if their program is at risk of losing eligibility.

**Sec. 85001. Delay of Rule Relating to Borrower Defense to Repayment.**
The bill delays the implementation of the November 1, 2022, regulations regarding borrower defense to repayment for loans originating before July 1, 2035, effectively reverting to the rules in effect on July 1, 2020. This suspension prevents the more expansive borrower defense provisions from applying to new loans for over a decade, limiting the ability of borrowers to have loans discharged based on institutional misconduct. The change restores the stricter standards that were in place prior to the 2022 regulatory updates.

**Sec. 85002. Delay of Rule Relating to Closed School Discharges.**
Similar to borrower defense, the bill delays the November 1, 2022, regulations regarding closed school loan discharges for loans originating before July 1, 2035, reverting to the previous regulatory framework. This action prevents the automatic or streamlined discharge provisions for students whose schools closed from applying to new loans for the next decade. The measure aims to reduce the financial liability on the federal government for closed school discharges under the new, more lenient rules.

**Sec. 86001. Garden of Heroes.**
The bill appropriates $40,000,000 to the National Endowment for the Humanities for fiscal year 2025 to fund the procurement of statues for the National Garden of American Heroes. These funds remain available through fiscal year 2028 and are designated for building monuments to American heroes as directed by Executive Orders 13934, 13978, and 14189. The appropriation supports the creation of physical memorials celebrating American history and values.

**Sec. 87001. Potential Sponsor Vetting for Unaccompanied Alien Children Appropriation.**
The bill appropriates $300,000,000 to the Office of Refugee Resettlement for fiscal year 2025 to fund enhanced vetting processes for potential sponsors of unaccompanied alien children. These funds must be used for comprehensive background checks, home studies, gang-related tattoo examinations, data system improvements, and coordination with state child welfare agencies. The appropriation ensures that sponsors and their households undergo rigorous screening, including criminal history checks and suitability studies, before a child is placed in their care. [end of text]


